To address the accessibility issue regarding the missing descriptive text for each link, based on the Web Content Accessibility Guidelines (WCAG) 2.1, we need to add meaningful text within each hyperlink that clearly explains the destination or purpose of the link. The use of only icons inside the links without any textual description can make it challenging for screen readers and users with accessibility needs to understand the purpose of each link. Here is how you can modify the source code to meet the WCAG 2.1 guidelines for descriptive link text:

```html
<a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="https://twitter.com/plex" data-pulldown="item-social-x" aria-label="Follow Plex on Twitter"><i class="icomoon icon-social-x"></i><span class="visually-hidden">Twitter</span></a>, 
<a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="https://www.facebook.com/plexapp" data-pulldown="item-social-facebook" aria-label="Follow Plex on Facebook"><i class="icomoon icon-social-facebook"></i><span class="visually-hidden">Facebook</span></a>, 
<a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="https://www.instagram.com/plex.tv/" data-pulldown="item-social-instagram" aria-label="Follow Plex on Instagram"><i class="icomoon icon-social-instagram"></i><span class="visually-hidden">Instagram</span></a>, 
<a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="https://www.tiktok.com/@plex.tv" data-pulldown="item-social-tiktok" aria-label="Follow Plex on TikTok"><i class="icomoon icon-social-tiktok"></i><span class="visually-hidden">TikTok</span></a>, 
<a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="https://www.linkedin.com/company/plex-inc" data-pulldown="item-social-linkedin" aria-label="Follow Plex on LinkedIn"><i class="icomoon icon-social-linkedin"></i><span class="visually-hidden">LinkedIn</span></a>, 
<a target="_blank" rel="noopener" href="https://www.youtube.com/user/plextvapp" data-pulldown="item-social-youtube" aria-label="Follow Plex on YouTube"><i class="icomoon icon-social-youtube"></i><span class="visually-hidden">YouTube</span></a>
```

**Explanation and Changes Made:**

1. **Aria-label**: Added `aria-label` attributes to each link to provide descriptive text for screen readers. This helps users understand the purpose of the link without seeing the icon. For example, `aria-label="Follow Plex on Twitter"` clearly describes the action and target.

2. **Visually Hidden Text**: Added `<span class="visually-hidden">...</span>` elements with textual descriptions (e.g., "Twitter", "Facebook") inside each link. This is for screen readers to read the text, making the purpose of the link accessible. Styles for `.visually-hidden` should be defined in CSS in such a way that the text is accessible to screen readers but not visible on the screen, ensuring that the visual design remains unchanged.

Here’s an example CSS for the `.visually-hidden` class:

```css
.visually-hidden {
    position: absolute;
    width: 1px;
    height: 1px;
    margin: -1px;
    padding: 0;
    overflow: hidden;
    clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
    border: 0;
}
```

By making these adjustments, you ensure that the links are accessible to users with disabilities, complying with WCAG 2.1 requirements for link text.
